Node.Notes: Probably the tune to which the psalm was sung, which seems to be literally "the lily of testimony."
Irregular spelling for "heal/make whole," but probably correct.
Uncertain. Could be "that it [the banner] may be displayed because of the truth/to be unfurled against the bow/that they may flee to it from the bow."
Uncertain. Could be derived from two roots, one (unfurl [a banner] or assemble [under a banner]), another (flee).

Uncertain. Some link to custom of victorious king placing foot on defeated enemy’s neck as sign of victory; others to a slave assigned to carry his master's sandals. Majority link to custom of taking off a sandal as a sign of ownership (Deut 25:9-10; Ruth 4:7).
Many prefer to conform this to Hebrew text of ps108:9: "I will shout in triumph over Philistia." Text here perhaps workable as "Acclaim me with shouts of joy, O Philistia!"
Context suggests reference to Sela, the strongly defended capital of Edom, in a military conquest of Edom.
